excerpt: Includes the city's art and design collections and a special Sherlock Holmes trail in the grounds.
detail_description: Portsmouth Museum and Art Gallery is a free cultural institution located in a grand Victorian building that offers visitors an opportunity to delve into the city's rich history and cultural heritage. The museum features themed displays and exhibits, including recreated rooms of dockyard workers' kitchens and 1950s living rooms, as well as a football exhibition showcasing Portsmouth's identity.
name: Portsmouth Museum and Art Gallery
address: Museum Rd, Portsmouth, PO1 2LJ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Landmark tower with an on-site cafe and a glass-floored platform overlooking Portsmouth harbour.
detail_description: The Spinnaker Tower, a prominent landmark in Portsmouth, offers visitors an unforgettable experience. Standing at 170 meters tall, it provides stunning 360-degree views of Portsmouth Harbour, the South coast, and the Isle of Wight. The tower features a glass-floored platform and an on-site cafe for visitors to enjoy. Constructed with an elegant design, it has become a national icon for Britain since its opening in October 2005.
name: Spinnaker Tower
address: Portsmouth, PO1 3TT, United Kingdom

excerpt: Historic area with iconic attractions like Nelson's HMS Victory, HMS Warrior & the Mary Rose Museum.
detail_description: The Portsmouth Historic Dockyard is a must-visit destination, featuring three renowned ships: The Mary Rose, HMS Victory, and HMS Warrior. The Mary Rose Museum offers a fascinating glimpse into Tudor life with over 19,000 artifacts on display alongside the well-preserved warship. Visitors can explore nine galleries showcasing the ship's history. Meanwhile, HMS Victory is famous for its role in the Battle of Trafalgar and now features an under hull walkway for a unique perspective.
name: Portsmouth Historic Dockyard
address: Victory Gate, HM Naval Base, Portsea, Portsmouth PO1 3LJ, United Kingdom

detail_description: Gunwharf Quays is not just a premier shopping center on the south coast, but also an entertainment hub. With over 90 stores, including outlet stores offering significant discounts, it's a shopper's paradise. The complex also boasts numerous cafes, bars, and restaurants such as Brasserie Blanc and Loch Fyne. Additionally, visitors can enjoy a Vue cinema complex, Hollywood Bowl, contemporary art gallery, nightclub and casino all in one place.
name: Gunwharf Quays
address: Portsmouth, UK

excerpt: Museum for 16th-century Tudor warship, & King Henry VIII's favourite, built in 1510 & sunk in 1545.
detail_description: The Mary Rose Museum is a must-visit for history enthusiasts, offering a glimpse into the 16th-century Tudor warship that was King Henry VIII's favorite. The museum showcases the preserved wreck of the ship, which was built in 1510 and sunk in 1545. Its modern architectural design mirrors traditional English boat sheds, while its interior features advanced climate control technology to preserve the ancient artifact.
name: Mary Rose Museum
address: Main Rd, HM Naval Base, Portsmouth PO1 3PY, United Kingdom

excerpt: D-Day story told through archive films, landing craft, weapons and the 83-metre Overlord Embroidery.
detail_description: The D-Day Story, located in Portsmouth, United Kingdom, is a museum that commemorates the allied effort to defeat Nazi Germany during World War II. Opened in 1984, the museum features the impressive 83-meter Overlord Embroidery which depicts the events of D-Day. Visitors can explore galleries with archived film footage and wartime images, providing a deeper understanding of the experiences of allied combat troops during this historic conflict.
name: The D-Day Story
address: Clarence Esplanade, Southsea, Portsmouth PO5 3NT, United Kingdom

excerpt: Pale-stone, Anglican cathedral in a 12th-century setting, plus lunchtime recitals for a fee.
detail_description: Portsmouth Cathedral, also known as the Cathedral Church of St. Thomas of Canterbury, has a rich history dating back to 1188 when the first chapel was established on its site. Over the centuries, it evolved from a parish church to gaining cathedral status in 1927.
name: Portsmouth Cathedral
address: High St, Old Portsmouth, Portsmouth PO1 2HA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Modern mall with stores including designer fashion retailers, plus bars, cafes and restaurants.
detail_description: Gunwharf Quays is a modern shopping center located in Portsmouth, offering a wide range of designer fashion retailers, as well as bars, cafes, and restaurants. It's an ideal destination for those seeking retail therapy or looking for luxury shopping experiences. The center also features additional attractions such as a cinema, bowling alley, and art gallery. Situated by the water with outdoor seating options available, it provides a pleasant environment to enjoy good weather while taking in beautiful harbor views.
name: Gunwharf Quays
address: Portsmouth, PO1 3TZ, United Kingdom

excerpt: The house where Dickens was born, furnished in Regency style and open from March to September.
detail_description: The Charles Dickens' Birthplace Museum, located at 393 Old Commercial Road in Portsmouth, is the former home of the legendary English novelist. The house has been meticulously restored and furnished in Regency style to reflect the middle-class tastes of Dickens' era. Visitors can explore the museum from March to September and gain insight into the early life of this celebrated writer.
name: Charles Dickens' Birthplace Museum
address: 393 Old Commercial Rd, Portsmouth, PO1 4QL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Old Portsmouth is a district of the city of Portsmouth. It is the area covered by the original medieval town of Portsmouth as planned by Jean de Gisors. It is situated in the south west corner of Portsea Island. The roads still largely follow their original layout. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Old Portsmouth is a historic district located in the southwest corner of Portsea Island, originally planned by Jean de Gisors. The area retains its medieval layout, with roads following their original design. The Round Tower and Square Tower, dating back to the 15th century, stand as guardians at the entrance to the city's harbor and naval dockyards.
name: Old Portsmouth
address: Portsmouth, UK

excerpt: Britain's first iron-hulled, armoured warship and pride of the fleet with an on-site visitor centre.
detail_description: HMS Warrior is a significant piece of British naval history, being the country's first iron-hulled, armoured battleship. Located at Portsmouth's Historic Dockyard alongside other famous vessels like HMS Victory and The Mary Rose, it offers visitors a chance to step aboard and explore its well-preserved interior. Unlike guided tours, visitors can freely roam the ship using a provided layout guide. Additionally, the on-site visitor center provides further insight into the ship's storied past.
name: HMS Warrior
address: Victory Gate, Portsmouth, PO1 3QX, United Kingdom

excerpt: Seasonal rides & an upside-down house, plus year-round arcades & an indoor playground.
detail_description: Clarence Pier is a popular destination on the south coast, offering seasonal rides, an upside-down house, arcades, and an indoor playground. Originally opened in 1861 and later rebuilt in the 1960s after being bombed during World War Two, it's now a hub of activity with diverse events throughout the year. It's not just for kids; it's also a great spot for a fun date.
name: Clarence Pier
address: Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea, PO5 3AA, United Kingdom

detail_description: Canoe Lake, located in Southsea, is a charming and picturesque spot perfect for a relaxing day out. The lake features swan-shaped pedal boats that are enjoyable for both kids and adults. The surrounding park is well-maintained with plenty of seating, lovely flower beds, and a playground for the kids. Visitors can take peaceful walks, feed the ducks, or enjoy snacks at the nearby cafe.
name: Canoe Lake
address: Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea, PO4 9RG, UK

excerpt: Victorian theatre presenting touring and home-grown drama, music and comedy, plus workshops.
detail_description: New Theatre Royal is a stunning Grade II* listed Victorian theatre situated in the heart of Portsmouth. With a seating capacity for up to 640 patrons, it boasts a beautiful auditorium designed by renowned Victorian architects Charles Phipps and Frank Matcham. The theater offers an eclectic mix of performances, including drama, music, comedy, and workshops. From community shows to professional dance and family performances, there's something for everyone. Visitors can expect high-quality entertainment ranging from tribute shows to professional productions.
name: New Theatre Royal
address: 20-24 Guildhall Walk, Portsmouth, PO1 2DD, United Kingdom

detail_description: Kings Theatre offers a diverse range of entertainment, including music, drama, and dance performances. The venue is housed in a beautifully restored Grade II* listed Edwardian theater. In addition to its entertainment program, Kings Theatre also engages with the community through educational initiatives and partnerships with youth and professional organizations. This ensures that the theater remains an integral part of the local cultural scene.
name: Kings Theatre
address: Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea, United Kingdom

excerpt: This famous church built in the early 1200s & used as an almshouse & hospice was firebombed in WWII.
detail_description: The Royal Garrison Church, also known as Domus Dei, is a historic site in Portsmouth with a rich and varied past. Originally built in the early 1200s as an almshouse and hospice for overseas pilgrims, it later served as an armory after the Dissolution of the Monasteries by King Henry VIII. The church was witness to significant events such as the wedding ceremony of King Charles II and Princess Catherine of Braganza in 1662.
name: English Heritage - Royal Garrison Church
address: Portsmouth, PO1 2NJ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Naval and archaeological exhibits plus interactive schools' tours in Henry VIII's moated castle.
detail_description: Southsea Castle, located in the charming town of Portsmouth, is a historical fortress built by King Henry VIII in 1544 as part of England's coastal defense system. The castle offers naval and archaeological exhibits, interactive school tours, and panoramic views of the Solent and the Isle of Wight. Over the centuries, it has been strengthened to protect Portsmouth from invaders. Today, visitors can enjoy a welcoming experience with features such as an on-site microbrewery and summer champagne evenings.
name: Southsea Castle
address: Unnamed Road, Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea PO5 3PA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Museum within the world's oldest commissioned warship which gained fame at the Battle of Trafalgar.
detail_description: HMS Victory is a museum housed within the oldest commissioned warship in the world, known for its role in the Battle of Trafalgar. Commissioned by King George III in 1758, this historic vessel offers an awe-inspiring journey through its decks and crew's quarters. It was Lord Nelson's flagship during the famous battle, and visitors can explore its impressive structure filled with cannons and paraphernalia for an 850-strong crew.
name: HMS Victory
address: Main Rd, HM Naval Base, Portsmouth PO1 3LJ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Local fish, sharks and rays, tropical species in an ocean display, plus underwater viewing tunnel.
detail_description: Blue Reef Aquarium Portsmouth is a captivating family attraction that offers an immersive experience with marine life. Situated between South Parade pier and Clarence pier, it provides an educational opportunity to learn about marine life along the British coast and the Mediterranean. With over 40 displays, visitors can gain a deeper appreciation of the incredible variety of marine life worldwide. The aquarium features open-top tanks where guests can get up close with stingrays, tide-pool inhabitants, sharks, and coral reef fish.
name: Blue Reef Aquarium Portsmouth
address: Clarence Esplanade, Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea PO5 3PB, United Kingdom

detail_description: The Portsmouth Natural History Museum offers a fascinating exploration of local habitats, showcasing how wildlife adapts to both natural and urban environments. Visitors can enjoy the butterfly house and a range of exhibits, including the A-Z of Natural History with intriguing specimens like puffer fish and Kiwi birds. The museum also features an observational beehive for an inside look at honey-making processes.
name: Portsmouth Natural History Museum
address: A288, Southsea, Portsmouth, Southsea PO4 9RF, UK
